        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Numerical code verification acceptance criteria — MRL 2",
        "description": "Vendor-supplied method of manufactured solutions (MMS) test suite for incompressible Navier-Stokes confirms expected spatial and temporal order of accuracy. Gradation 2 achieved."
      },
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent's published MMS verification suite demonstrates second-order spatial accuracy for the pressure-velocity coupling scheme used in this study. No bespoke solver modifications were made; vendor verification documentation accepted per MRL 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/disc-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/disc-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Discretization error acceptance criteria — MRL 2",
        "description": "Grid convergence index (GCI) < 5% for hemolysis index QoI across three systematically refined meshes (coarse 2.1 M, medium 5.8 M, fine 14.2 M cells). GCI achieved < 3.1% at the fine-mesh level."
      },
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study performed at the nominal operating point (3 L/min, 3500 RPM). GCI computed per Celik et al. (2008) protocol: GCI_fine = 3.1% for the normalized hemolysis index, satisfying the < 5% acceptance criterion. Medium mesh (5.8 M cells) adopted for production runs as the fine-mesh solution is within GCI bounds."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/test-conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/test-conditions",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test conditions acceptance criteria — MRL 2",
        "description": "Experimental hemolysis measurements conducted with bovine blood at 37 °C, hematocrit 33 ± 2%, under ISO 10628-compliant recirculation loop. Boundary conditions in CFD set to match measured inlet velocity profiles and outlet static pressure."
      },
      "rationale": "FDA GCBP experimental dataset (Hariharan et al., 2011) documents test fluid properties, temperature, hematocrit, and flow-loop configuration. CFD inlet boundary conditions derived from LDV measurements at the pump inlet plane; outlet pressure matched to experimental back-pressure gauge readings. Gradation 2 achieved: documented correspondence between test and simulation boundary conditions."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/output-comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/output-comparison",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison acceptance criteria — MRL 2",
        "description": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) compared against experimental NIH measurements at 5 operating points. Agreement within ±25% at all points; mean absolute percentage error ≤ 15%."
      },
      "rationale": "CFD-predicted NIH values at all five operating points (2, 3, 4, 5, 6 L/min at 3500 RPM) fall within ±20% of the experimental measurements from Hariharan et al. Mean absolute percentage error is 12.4%. The relative hemolysis index RH < 1 at all test-article operating points relative to the predicate device, satisfying the primary acceptance criterion."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/qoi-relevance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/qoi-relevance",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance acceptance criteria — MRL 2",
        "description": "Primary QoI (NIH and relative hemolysis index RH) are direct clinical surrogates for pump-induced hemolysis. Secondary QoIs (wall shear stress distribution, scalar stress exposure) are mechanistically linked to the Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis power-law model used in the CFD."
      },
      "rationale": "NIH is the FDA-accepted metric for hemolysis evaluation in blood-contacting devices (FDA guidance, 2021). RH < 1 is a recognized comparative acceptance criterion for predicate-device comparisons. The scalar stress exposure (SSE) field output is the direct input to the power-law hemolysis damage model, establishing mechanistic traceability from simulation output to clinical endpoint."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/val-relevance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/val-relevance",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation relevance acceptance criteria — MRL 2",
        "description": "Validation experiments performed on the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump — the same geometry as the COU device — under CPB-representative flow conditions (2–6 L/min, 3500 RPM). Validation domain spans the COU operating envelope."
      },
      "rationale": "The FDA GCBP benchmark is geometrically identical to the device under assessment. Operating conditions in the validation dataset (2–6 L/min, 3500 RPM) bracket the five COU operating points, ensuring the validation domain fully covers the intended use envelope. The same turbulence model (SST k-ω) and hemolysis damage model are used in both validation and COU simulations, preserving modelling fidelity."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/num-solver-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "At MRL 2, numerical solver error beyond discretization error and code verification is scoped out. The commercial solver (ANSYS Fluent) provides no accessible iterative-error decomposition beyond residual monitoring; residuals converged to < 1×10⁻⁵ for all equations at all operating points, consistent with MRL 2 expectations. A separate solver-error characterization study is not warranted at this risk level."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Use error assessment (independent re-analysis by a second analyst) is scoped out at MRL 2. The simulation setup was reviewed by a senior engineer against the documented simulation plan, and all boundary conditions, material properties, and solver settings were verified via checklist. A full independent re-run is reserved for MRL 3+ assessments."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/model-form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty (e.g., alternative turbulence model comparisons, alternative hemolysis damage model comparisons) is scoped out at MRL 2. The SST k-ω turbulence model and Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model are the consensus choices for this class of blood pump CFD per the FDA GCBP benchmark literature. Systematic model-form uncertainty quantification is deferred to MRL 3."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/model-inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Formal model input uncertainty propagation (e.g., Monte Carlo over blood viscosity, hematocrit, geometry tolerances) is scoped out at MRL 2. Nominal input values are taken from the FDA GCBP benchmark specification and are well-characterised. Sensitivity of NIH to ±5% variation in viscosity was checked informally and found to be < 3%; full UQ is deferred to MRL 3."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/test-samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Test sample characterisation (e.g., lot-to-lot blood variability, device-to-device geometric variability) is scoped out at MRL 2. The FDA GCBP benchmark uses a single representative geometry and a standardised bovine blood protocol; variability across test samples is not the primary source of uncertainty at this model risk level."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/equiv-input-params",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters between the validation experiment and the COU simulation is scoped out at MRL 2 beyond what is captured under Test Conditions. The FDA GCBP benchmark geometry, fluid properties, and operating conditions are sufficiently representative of the COU that a formal equivalency mapping exercise is not required at this risk level. Residual differences (e.g., minor inlet turbulence intensity assumptions) are within the ±25% output comparison tolerance."
    }
